Demea on the contrary had kept up the thrifty habits of his early years, residing on his farm and taking a severe view of the conduct of his sons. Ctesipho, the younger of his sons, lived with his father at this farm; but Aeschinus, the elder, had been adopted by his uncle. They had accordingly been very differ· ently brought up. Ctesipho had been kept very strictly at home, and was, to the best of his father’s belief, a model of propriety. Aeschinus had been indulged by his uncle in every way, till he was notorious for his dissipation.
